Threat Modeling Report

Created on 24.10.2024 8:22:43

Threat Model Name: E-doklady

Owner: Jan Kubíček

Reviewer:

Contributors:

Description: Národní systém pro správu Elektronické verze dokladů realizovaná ČR. Pro účely modelu je vycházeno z následujících axiomů: Systém je realizován v jazyce Java a JavaScript s využitím webových technologií Spring boot. Bezpečnost ( uživatelské role, realizace tokenů/session) zajištuje Spring boot Security. Informace o uživateli jsou uložené v databázi SQL Server. Fotografie uživatele jsou také uložené v databázi SQL ve formátu (Base64). Části a jejich funkcionalita: 1. Hranice Prohlizece - Jedná se o lokální instanci prohlížeče s uložištěm v rámci jehož jsou Cookies. 2. Hranice Mobilního telefonu - Z důvodu mobility je umožňěn přístup i prostřednictvím mobilních zařízení. 3. Hranice Internetu - Rozděluje Lokální zařízení a Vzdálenou část internetu. 4. Produkční Server - Poukazuje na fakt, že následné body 5. a 6. jsou uloženy v rámci jednoho serveru. 5. Datové uložiště serveru - Zde je uložen konfigurační soubor serveru a také zde jsou uloženy statické webové stránky (neposkytují žádnou službu). 6. Aplikační Kontainer - Zajištuje naslouchání na předem vybraných EndPointech, které jsou obsluhovány pomocí realizovaných Služeb. 6.1. Datové Centrum - Jedná se o uložení veškerých klientských dat, které poskytly systému.

Assumptions:

External Dependencies: Další materiály: SekvenčníDiagram08new.drawio.png (Registrace uživatele) SekvenčníDiagram09new.drawio.png (Přihlášení uživatele) SekvenčníDiagram10new.drawio.png (Uložení dat v lokálním uložišti telefonu) Funkce systému E-doklady: https://edoklady.gov.cz https://www.usetreno.cz/clanky/edoklady/ https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=lYhDog1XdLs

Interaction: gRPC volání

1. Authorization Bypass  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Can you access Cloud Audit Logging and bypass the permissions for the object? For example by editing the files directly with a hex editor, or reaching it via filesharing? Ensure that your program is the only one that can access the data, and that all other subjects have to use your interface.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

2. Data Store Denies Cloud Audit Logging Potentially Writing Data  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Cloud Audit Logging claims that it did not write data received from an entity on the other side of the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

3. Potential Weak Protections for Audit Data  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Consider what happens when the audit mechanism comes under attack, including attempts to destroy the logs, or attack log analysis programs. Ensure access to the log is through a reference monitor, which controls read and write separately. Document what filters, if any, readers can rely on, or writers should expect
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

4. Insufficient Auditing  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Does the log capture enough data to understand what happened in the past? Do your logs capture enough data to understand an incident after the fact? Is such capture lightweight enough to be left on all the time? Do you have enough data to deal with repudiation claims? Make sure you log sufficient and appropriate data to handle a repudiation claims. You might want to talk to an audit expert as well as a privacy expert about your choice of data.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

5. Data Logs from an Unknown Source  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Do you accept logs from unknown or weakly authenticated users or systems? Identify and authenticate the source of the logs before accepting them.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

6. Lower Trusted Subject Updates Logs  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:If you have trust levels, is anyone other outside of the highest trust level allowed to log? Letting everyone write to your logs can lead to repudiation problems. Only allow trusted code to log.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Repudiation threats involve an adversary denying that something happened.

7. The Cloud Audit Logging Data Store Could Be Corrupted  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across gRPC volání may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to corruption of Cloud Audit Logging. Ensure the integrity of the data flow to the data store.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

8. Risks from Logging  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Log readers can come under attack via log files. Consider ways to canonicalize data in all logs. Implement a single reader for the logs, if possible, in order to reduce attack surface area. Be sure to understand and document log file elements which come from untrusted sources.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

9. Spoofing of Destination Data Store Cloud Audit Logging  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Cloud Audit Logging may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Cloud Audit Logging. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Spoofing is when a process or entity is something other than its claimed identity. Examples include substituting a process, a file, website or a network address.

10. Weak Credential Storage  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Credentials held at the server are often disclosed or tampered with and credentials stored on the client are often stolen. For server side, consider storing a salted hash of the credentials instead of storing the credentials themselves. If this is not possible due to business requirements, be sure to encrypt the credentials before storage, using an SDL-approved mechanism. For client side, if storing credentials is required, encrypt them and protect the data store in which they're stored
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

11. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Server or Cloud Audit Logging  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Server or Cloud Audit Logging take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

12. Data Flow gRPC volání Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

13. Data Store Inaccessible  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent prevents access to a data store on the other side of the trust boundary.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

14. Weak Authentication Scheme  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Custom authentication schemes are susceptible to common weaknesses such as weak credential change management, credential equivalence, easily guessable credentials, null credentials, downgrade authentication or a weak credential change management system. Consider the impact and potential mitigations for your custom authentication scheme.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

15. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Attackers who can send a series of packets or messages may be able to overlap data. For example, packet 1 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 0. Packet 2 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 25. Packet 2 will overwrite 75 bytes of packet 1. Ensure you reassemble data before filtering it, and ensure you explicitly handle these sorts of cases.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

16. Replay Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Packets or messages without sequence numbers or timestamps can be captured and replayed in a wide variety of ways. Implement or utilize an existing communication protocol that supports anti-replay techniques (investigate sequence numbers before timers) and strong integrity.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

17. WAF (Webový aplikační Firewall) Process Memory Tampered  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:If WAF (Webový aplikační Firewall) is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what Klient Prohlizece executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then WAF (Webový aplikační Firewall) can tamper with Klient Prohlizece. Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

123. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High]

For client side, if storing credentials is required, encrypt them and protect the data store in which they're stored

235. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High]

Justification:<no mitigation provided>

Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Denial of Service happens when the process or a datastore is not able to service incoming requests or perform up to spec.

268. Weak Credential Storage  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Credentials held at the server are often disclosed or tampered with and credentials stored on the client are often stolen. For server side, consider storing a salted hash of the credentials instead of storing the credentials themselves. If this is not possible due to business requirements, be sure to encrypt the credentials before storage, using an SDL-approved mechanism. For client side, if storing credentials is required, encrypt them and protect the data store in which they're stored
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

269. Authorization Bypass  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Can you access SQL Server DBS and bypass the permissions for the object? For example by editing the files directly with a hex editor, or reaching it via filesharing? Ensure that your program is the only one that can access the data, and that all other subjects have to use your interface.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Information disclosure happens when the information can be read by an unauthorized party.

272. Potential SQL Injection Vulnerability for SQL Server DBS  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:SQL injection is an attack in which malicious code is inserted into strings that are later passed to an instance of SQL Server for parsing and execution. Any procedure that constructs SQL statements should be reviewed for injection vulnerabilities because SQL Server will execute all syntactically valid queries that it receives. Even parameterized data can be manipulated by a skilled and determined attacker.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

280. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High]

Description:If Mobilní applikace is given access to memory, such as shared memory or pointers, or is given the ability to control what WAF (Webový aplikační Firewall) executes (for example, passing back a function pointer.), then Mobilní applikace can tamper with WAF (Webový aplikační Firewall). Consider if the function could work with less access to memory, such as passing data rather than pointers. Copy in data provided, and then validate it.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

397. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Attackers who can send a series of packets or messages may be able to overlap data. For example, packet 1 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 0. Packet 2 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 25. Packet 2 will overwrite 75 bytes of packet 1. Ensure you reassemble data before filtering it, and ensure you explicitly handle these sorts of cases.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

398. Replay Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Packets or messages without sequence numbers or timestamps can be captured and replayed in a wide variety of ways. Implement or utilize an existing communication protocol that supports anti-replay techniques (investigate sequence numbers before timers) and strong integrity.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
Short Description:Tampering is the act of altering the bits. Tampering with a process involves changing bits in the running process. Similarly, Tampering with a data flow involves changing bits on the wire or between two running processes.

420. Weak Credential Storage  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Credentials held at the server are often disclosed or tampered with and credentials stored on the client are often stolen. For server side, consider storing a salted hash of the credentials instead of storing the credentials themselves. If this is not possible due to business requirements, be sure to encrypt the credentials before storage, using an SDL-approved mechanism. For client side, if storing credentials is required, encrypt them and protect the data store in which they're stored
Justification:<no mitigation provided>
